irnshire, Scotland","Duntreath Castle, Strathblane, Stirlingshire, Schotland":"Strathblane, Stirlingshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Edmonstone","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish:  see  Edmonston  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edmonston","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Edmiston  ."]}]},{"name":"Liard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Etienne, Richet.","Americanized form of German   Leinert  .","French: from the personal name <i>Linard</i>, a variant of   Leonard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Leinert","meanings":["(2010: NA)","German: variant of   Lienert  . Compare   Leinart   and   Linard  ."]}]},{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Dunreath","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: from a Scottish Gaelic name imported from Scotland to Northern Ireland in the 17th century. The evidence suggests that the surname derives from an unidentified Gaelic placename, probably in southwest Scotland, <i>Dún Sídhe</i> or the like."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunshee","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Dunseath  . The spelling <i>Dunseath</i> represents an older Anglicization than <i>Dunshee</i>."]}]},{"name":"en","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Juel.","Norwegian (<b>Øen</b>): habitational name from the farm name Øen, found in several places. In Hornindal in Nordfjord and in Ål in Hallingdal it is from <i>øy</i> ‘meadow by water’, in Hyllestad in Sunnfjord from <i>å</i> ‘small river’ + Old Norse <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’, in other places from the definite singular form of <i>øy</i> ‘island’.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Oen in Hordaland, from Old Norse <i>Ó</i>, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Wen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Han, Cheng, Jin, Li, Yen, Yong, Chen, Chih-Hung, Chin, Hong, Jian, Jung, Long, Huan, Hung, Hung Chi, Ly, Quan.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 溫, meaning ‘warm’ in Chinese: (i) from Wen (溫), the name of an ancient state during the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ). During the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) this state was annexed by the state of Di and the prince of Wen fled to the state of Wey (located around present-day Hebi and Xinxiang in Henan province). His descendants acquired 溫, the name of their original state, as their surname. (ii) from the placename Wen (溫), the name of a fief granted to Wen Ji (溫季), an official in the state of Jin (located mainly in present-day Shanxi province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iii) from the Chi Wen (叱溫), Wen Pen (溫盆), and Wen Gu (溫孤) families of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iv) from the personal name of Wen Sheng (溫昇), who went into exile and changed his original surname, Liu (劉), to Wen 溫 after his father, Liu Yicong (劉易從), an official in the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ), suffered persecution and death."]}]},{"name":"Willem","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Willem Edmonstone Liard van Dunreath en Culloden was born in 1390, in Nairnshire, Scotland as the son of Sir Archibald Edmonstone and Janet Shaw. He married Princess Mary Stewart Countess of Angus in 1425, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1460, in Strathblane, Stirlingshire, Scotland, at the age of 70."},"et":{"1390–1460":"1390–1460","1380–1457":"1380–1457","1420–1500":"1420–1500","1427–1486":"1427–1486","–Female":"Surnud","1345–1415":"1345–1415","10 December 1427":"10. detsember 1427","1460":"1460","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1425":"1425","1457":"1457","1500":"1500","1345":"1345","1420":"1420","1486":"1486","20 Mar 1457":"20. märts 1457","1427":"1427","Leckie, Scotland":"Scotland","Duntreath, , Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Duntreath, Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Duntreath, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Duntreath, Stirlingshire, Scotland","Culloden, Nairnshire, Scotland":"Nairnshire, Scotland","Duntreath Castle, Strathblane, Stirlingshire, Schotland":"Strathblane, Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1390–1460":"1390–1460","1380–1457":"1380–1457","1420–1500":"1420–1500","1427–1486":"1427–1486","–Female":"Kuollut","1345–1415":"1345–